{
    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect timer callback execution in NAS timer management\n\n### Summary\nThe NAS timer system was not executing the correct timer callbacks when multiple timers were active. The `nas_timer_handle_signal_expiry` function was always calling the callback of the first timer in the queue instead of finding and executing the callback for the specific timer that expired.\n\nThis issue was caused by the timer expiration handler not properly matching the ITTI timer_id with the corresponding NAS timer entry. Additionally, the NAS UE task was not processing TIMER_HAS_EXPIRED messages from the ITTI system.\n\nThe bug manifested when multiple EMM procedures with different timers (T3410, T3411, etc.) were running simultaneously - only the first timer's callback would execute regardless of which timer actually expired.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/COMMON/UTIL/nas_timer.c`: Rewrote `nas_timer_handle_signal_expiry` to properly find and execute the callback for the expired timer based on its ITTI timer_id\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/nas_ue_task.c`: Added handling for TIMER_HAS_EXPIRED messages to call the NAS timer expiry handler\n- `openair3/NAS/COMMON/UTIL/nas_timer.h`: Made `nas_timer_handle_signal_expiry` available in all NAS contexts by removing conditional compilation\n\n"
}